@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------------------- Usage -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Main" "Usage"
@{U}3) Using Laplace@{UU}

   Laplace works much like a shell, you enter an expression, press return  and
Laplace gives you the result (after some time;-).

   To learn about  the input  format that  is used  to tell  Laplace, what  it
should do, have a look at the @{"expression syntax" LINK "Syntax.guide/Syntax"}.

   When a new window is opened,  Laplace confronts you with an empty  environ-
ment.  In  most  cases   you  will  include   the  standard  libraries   using
@{B}include("init.lh");@{UB}, that's why this  expression is always  inserted as a  de-
fault. You just have to press return to execute this expression, and  continue
with your work.

   To avoid confusion,  a line (consisting  of your input  and the result)  is
from now on called an @{I}entry @{UI}, because itself may consist of several @{I}lines @{UI}.

   Each entry consists of two parts: your input and the result. Your input may
consist of several line and always starts at an input prompt.

   @{" * " LINK "Structure"}  Hierarchical structure
   @{" * " LINK "GUI"}  The graphical interface
