@NODE "Structure"
@TITLE "Hierarchical structure"
@NEXT "GUI"
@TOC "Usage"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ------------------------------------ Hierarchical structure -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Usage" "Hierarchical structure"
@{U}3.1) Hierarchical structure@{UU}

   Laplace works strictly hierarchically. This  means that all the results  of
an entry can only influence the following entries. There is usually no way  to
have a @{I}backward effect @{UI}. If you define a variable or function, it can only  be
referenced from the following entries. In the preceding entries it's just  @{I}un-@{UI}
@{I}known @{UI}. If you later assign a new value to this variable, the old value is not
discarded; it can still be used in the intervening entries, e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} ...      (@{B}a@{UB} is unknown here)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a := 5;  (@{B}a@{UB} evaluates to 5)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} ...
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} ...
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} a := 7;  (@{B}a@{UB} now evaluates to 7, but remains 5 in the preceding entries)
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} ...


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "GUI"
@TITLE "The graphical interface"
@NEXT "Editmodes"
@PREV "Structure"
@TOC "Usage"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------- The graphical interface -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Usage" "The graphical interface"
@{U}3.2) The graphical interface@{UU}

   Laplace presents you a (hopefully) comfortable graphical interface. You can
open as many windows as you want, each window has it's own environment and you
can work with several projects simultaneously.

   Laplace features bubble help. Just leave  the mouse pointer on an item  and
wait a moment and a short description will be shown.

@{U}Edit windows@{UU}

   Each window is separated into three major parts: the @{"toolbar" LINK "Toolbar"} at the top, an
statusbar at the bottom and the main editing area in the middle.

   The leftmost field of the statusbar just displays whether you modified  the
current project since the last time that you saved it. It's right neighbour is
a cycle gadget that lets you select the current @{"editmode" LINK "Editmodes"}. The remaining  space
is filled by a text-field that displays the current cursor position.

   But the most interesting thing  is the big area that  fills up most of  the
window. Here the action takes place. You can scroll around in this area  using
the two sliders at the right and bottom. Laplace works just like a shell,  you
enter a command line, Laplace displays the result and you advance to the  next
line and so on. The main difference is that you can move up and make some mod-
ifications that may influence the results of the following lines.

@{U}The scheduler window@{UU}

   Apart from the windows, where you  enter your formulas, there is one  small
window that always appears,  while Laplace is running.  It's something like  a
@{I}main-control-panel @{UI}. At the bottom is a text field that displays the state  of
Laplace's calculation engine. Each time  when a calculation has finished,  the
elapsed time is displayed.  The @{B}abort@{UB}-button can only  be used with  asynchron
calculation; it will interrupt the current calculation.

   The scheduler window has it's own menu:

 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Project@{UB}
    @{B}À@{UB} @{B}About@{UB} - Show some information about Laplace.
    @{B}À@{UB} @{B}New window@{UB} - Open a new and empty window.
    @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Preferences...@{UB} -  This  will  open  the  preferences  window.  See
      @{"preferences" LINK "Preferences"} for more information.
    @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Quit@{UB} - Close  all windows and  exit Laplace. If  there are  recent
      changes, you will be asked whether  you want to save the  changes,
      but you @{I}cannot @{UI} abort this operation.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Hidden@{UB} This menu has  a special meaning.  If you @{I}hide  @{UI} an edit  window,
   it's title will appear in the menu. Selecting this entry will reopen the
   window.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Editmodes"
@TITLE "Editmodes"
@NEXT "History"
@PREV "GUI"
@TOC "Usage"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ------------------------------------------------- Editmodes -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Usage" "Editmodes"
@{U}3.3) Editmodes@{UU}

   Sometimes you want to enter a long  expression or a definition of a  proce-
dure. It would be quite annoying to  do this in a single line. Laplace  offers
two different modes for  this reason (the only  difference is the handling  of
the return-key). If you are in @{I}singleline mode @{UI}, pressing return tells Laplace
to evaluate the expression, return the result  to you and advance to the  next
entry. In @{I}multiline mode @{UI} return adds a  new line to the current entry in  the
same way as you know it from a usual text editor. You can split an  expression
at every point, where a space is allowed, Laplace doesn't distinguish  between
spaces and line breaks.

   Holding down the shift key reverses the effect: press shift-return to eval-
uate an expression while you are in  multiline mode, or to split a line  while
you are in singleline mode.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "History"
@TITLE "History"
@NEXT "Clipboard"
@PREV "Editmodes"
@TOC "Usage"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual --------------------------------------------------- History -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Usage" "History"
@{U}3.4) History@{UU}

   Laplace offers an easy way to copy some input that you already used before.
Hold down the control key and press the  up or down key. Then the contents  of
the succeeding or proceeding entry will be copied to the current entry. By re-
peatedly pressing the up/down key you can move further up or down in the  list
of entries.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Clipboard"
@TITLE "Clipboard"
@NEXT "Menu"
@PREV "History"
@TOC "Usage"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ------------------------------------------------- Clipboard -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Usage" "Clipboard"
@{U}3.5) Clipboard@{UU}

   Laplace supports the  global clipboard. You  can mark some  text using  the
@{"mouse" LINK "Mouse"} and then @{I}cut @{UI} it  out or just @{I}copy @{UI} it  to the clipboard. You can  later
@{I}paste @{UI} in  the contents of  the clipboard  at the cursor  position. Since  the
clipboard is global to all applications you can easily exchange short parts of
text between different programs. Laplace uses the clipboard unit zero.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Menu"
@TITLE "The menu"
@NEXT "Toolbar"
@PREV "Clipboard"
@TOC "Usage"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual -------------------------------------------------- The menu -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Usage" "The menu"
@{U}3.6) The menu@{UU}

   A menu is connected to each window.  Some actions only apply to the  active
window, but some are global to all windows (e.g. Quit ;-).

   Many menu items  have a keyboard  shortcut, e.g. @{B}A-l@{UB}  for @{B}Load...@{UB}:  Holding
down the right AMIGA-key  and pressing @{B}l@{UB} works  just like activating the  item
with your mouse.

   Some menu items  are marked by  some trailing dots,  like @{B}Save as...@{UB}.  This
means that more user  input is required, if  you select this entry.  Otherwise
some action is immediately performed.

   The menustrip is now fully  configurable. At this place  I will give you  a
description of the default configuration.

@{U}The @{B}Project@{UB} menu@{UU}

 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}About@{UB} - Show some information about Laplace.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}New window@{UB} - Open a new and empty window.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Open...@{UB} - Opens a requester where you can choose a project to be opened.
   If the current window is empty, it will be used, otherwise a new  window
   is opened.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Load...@{UB} - Similar to @{B}Open...@{UB}, except that it will always use the current
   window.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Save@{UB} - Save the current project under it's old name. If you haven't cho-
   sen a name for it, this works just like @{B}Save as...@{UB}
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Save as...@{UB} - Opens a  requester where you can  choose the path and  name
   for the current project and save it.  The selected name will be used  if
   you select @{B}Save@{UB} at a later moment.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Import...@{UB} - Read a project from an ASCII file.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Export...@{UB} - Write the current project as an ASCII file.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Hide@{UB} - This will temporarily close  the current window. A new menu  item
   in the @{B}Hidden@{UB}-menu of the scheduler window. Selecting this item will re-
   open the window.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Close@{UB} - Close the current window. If there are some recent changes  that
   are not saved, you will be asked what should be done. When you close the
   last window, Laplace will quit.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Quit@{UB} - Close all windows and exit  Laplace. Again you will be asked,  if
   there are recent changes, but you @{I}cannot @{UI} abort this operation.

@{U}The @{B}Edit@{UB} menu@{UU}

 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Mark all@{UB} - This marks  all characters of the  current entry, just as  if
   you used the mouse for this.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Unmark@{UB} - If there is  some text marked in  the current entry, this  mark
   will be removed.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Cut@{UB} - Cut out the currently marked text and copy it to the @{"clipboard" LINK "Clipboard"}.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Copy@{UB} - Copy  the currently  marked text to  the @{"clipboard" LINK "Clipboard"}  and leave  it
   where it is.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Paste@{UB} - The text  from the @{"clipboard" LINK "Clipboard"} is  inserted at the current  cursor
   position.

@{U}The @{B}Entries@{UB} menu@{UU}

 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Insert@{UB} - Insert a blank entry just before the current one, and make  the
   new one active.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Remove@{UB} - Removes the  current entry including it's  result (if there  is
   one).
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Remove all@{UB} - Clear all entries in the current window.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Clear result@{UB} - Discard the result  of the current entry. This will  also
   remove all definitions, options etc. associated with this entry.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Clear all results@{UB} -  Discard the results of  the all entries. This  will
   also remove all definitions, options etc.

@{U}The @{B}Preferences@{UB} menu@{UU}

 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Global...@{UB} - This will open  the preferences window. See @{"preferences" LINK "Preferences"}  for
   more information.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Plotter...@{UB} - Open the @{"settings window" LINK "Plotter.guide/PlotterSettings"} for the plotter. You can edit  the
   global settings that are used as default when a new plotter is opened.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Toolbar"
@TITLE "The toolbar"
@NEXT "Keyboard"
@PREV "Menu"
@TOC "Usage"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------------- The toolbar -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Usage" "The toolbar"
@{U}3.7) The toolbar@{UU}

   The toolbar at  the top of  each window offers  you a fast  access to  some
functions that are usually available in the menu.

   Just like the menu strip, you can configure the toolbar freely. Again, this
is only a description of the default configuration.

 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Cut@{UB} - Cut out the currently marked text and copy it to the clipboard.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Copy@{UB} - Copy  the currently  marked text to  the clipboard  and leave  it
   where it is.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Paste@{UB} - The text  from the clipboard is  inserted at the current  cursor
   position.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Preferences@{UB} - This will open the preferences window. See @{"preferences" LINK "Preferences"} for
   more information.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Keyboard"
@TITLE "The keyboard"
@NEXT "Mouse"
@PREV "Toolbar"
@TOC "Usage"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ---------------------------------------------- The keyboard -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Usage" "The keyboard"
@{U}3.8) The keyboard@{UU}

   Probably most work is done using your keyboard. I think that most functions
are straight ahead as you would expect  it (and know it from common text  edi-
tors), but you may adjust the keyboard mapping to your own requirements.

   If you are working with asynchron  calculation, you can interrupt the  cur-
rent  calculation  by   pressing  @{B}control-c@{UB}.  You   cannot  change  this   key
combination.

   If you enable @{I}erase block @{UI} in the preferences window and there is some text
marked, this text is replaced by your input. Without @{I}erase block @{UI} the mark  is
abolished.

   There are two unusual keys that Laplace uses:  @{B}Î@{UB} and @{B}▒@{UB}. @{B}Î@{UB} is not the  usual
x, but can be entered by @{B}alt-x@{UB}. To enter the ▒ sign press @{B}alt-y@{UB} on German key-
boards or @{B}alt-z@{UB} on other boards (the same key, just another label).

   Here is the key mapping of the default configuration:

 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}left@{UB}, @{B}right@{UB}, @{B}up@{UB}, @{B}down@{UB} - Cursor  movement. If you move across the  border
   of the current entry, you jump to the next/previous entry.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}shift-left@{UB}, @{B}shift-right@{UB} - Jump to the next/previous word.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}alt-left@{UB}, @{B}alt-right@{UB} - Jump to the beginning/end of the current line.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}shift-up@{UB}, @{B}shift-down@{UB} - Jump to the first/last line of the current entry.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}alt-up@{UB}, @{B}alt-down@{UB} - Jump to the entry that is just above/below the  visi-
   ble part.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}shift-alt-up@{UB}, @{B}shift-alt-down@{UB} - Jump to the first/last entry.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}control-up@{UB}, @{B}control-down@{UB} - Move one step forward/backward in the @{"history" LINK "History"}
   buffer.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}shift-control-up@{UB}, @{B}shift-control-down@{UB} - Move  to the first/last entry  in
   the @{"history" LINK "History"} buffer.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}backspace@{UB} - Delete the preceding character.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}shift-backspace@{UB} - Delete to the beginning of the current line.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}delete@{UB} - Delete the succeeding character.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}shift-delete@{UB} - Delete to the end of the current line.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}alt-delete@{UB} - Clear the result of the current entry.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}enter@{UB} - @{I}Singleline mode @{UI}: Evaluate  the current line and proceed to  the
   next entry. @{I}Multiline mode @{UI}: Insert a new line to the current entry.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}shift-enter@{UB} - @{I}Singleline mode @{UI}: Insert a new line to the current  entry.
   @{I}Multiline mode  @{UI}: Evaluate  the current  line and  proceed to  the  next
   entry.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mouse"
@TITLE "About mice and men..."
